metadata.name: Errors IV // Seasons
metadata.description:
The idea behind this project is to juxtapose two different frames from the same 'roll'. This is a double exposure experiment mixed using a few different blending modes. The double exposure is not done in camera, instead the algorithm will randomly pick two images and blend them.

In this section there are different images from different seasons, the opposition of some of the textures make some amazing ambience compositions. It's very interesting to visualize different distinctive features of each season mixed with each other. 

There are 36 different images on the 'film roll' so it's better to keep the editions low to avoid doubles as much as possible.

Unfortunately due to size restrictions of fxHash the images are not full size, and are limited to 1500px x 1000px.

metadata.name: The Seventh Circle
metadata.description:
The Seventh Circle

"Now I would have you know: the other time
that I descended into lower Hell,
this mass of boulders had not yet collapsed."


- The canvas is split into between 64 and 256 areas. Each area is separated from its neighbours by a border of between 1.5% and 4.5% of the canvas.

- Each area is further subdivided into between 64 and 100 smaller squares. These are separated by a proportionally-smaller border.

- A time-based function affects the hue of each square, mapping the sin and cosine of each squares position, offset by an amount determined from the initial hash. Over time, the colour of the squares will change, dependent on further initial values.

- Occasionally, sections of each grid will break away, rendering at an angle to the main piece. Within this, individual squares may be rotated slightly.

- The overlaid texture may be dark or bright, horizontally or vertically. The texture size may vary according to the initial conditions.


Most importantly, with the fullness of time, all pieces have a chance of returning to wholeness; they are all a part of a cycle of life, that each one may know its place.

Almost anything can be forgiven.

The intention in creating these works was to express a combination of chaos and order.

Line Balls is created by p5js.Each piece is 640 x 640.

Press 's' in live view to save the current image.

For each token, colors, noiseSeed, numbers of particles, lifes of particles, are generated, resulting in unique generative patterns for each minted item.

The minting price is low but the number of minting is large, so that everyone can explore more styles.

metadata.name: Fabrics
metadata.description:
Fabric. A collection of swatches. 

This is a project of stacked PNGs producing fabric swatches. Some are almost plaids, others are more batik, while others are more of a "magic eye" or optical illusion look. 

The PNGs were generated using VBA and conditional formatting in MS Excel, then copy/pasted as an image into MS PowerPoint, and occasionally further manipulated in different image editors including MS Paint. Images were batch resized to match each other at 1125x1125.

There are a lot of options for this collection. The layers and total number of options per (included "none" layers):
- Base
    - 42
- Flecking 
    - 18
- Broad
    - 50
- Underpin
    - 43
- Warp
    - 21
- Weft
    - 26
- Overpins
    - 43
- Mask
    - 21
- Texture
    - 14


There is a slight potential to mint the "imaginary fabric", one which is comprised of only "none" layers. That is the best of the bunch, because it is only limited by your imagination. Consider it the legendary.

There should be an interplay between the coded elements of each individual PNG and the overall stack. The randomness of coded layers stacked with other, dissimilar (base) coded layers generates interesting, and at times, colorful patterns that don't have a singular, obvious, overarching algo.

Hope you enjoy! 

Stacking achieved using PureSpider's pfp code https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

License CC BY-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Σ 360 Points of View
metadata.description:
What we see is normally a 2d projection from a 3d world. 
This is the representation of how things can be absorbed from our own perspective
and how important is to go all the way around, to move from our point of view.

Use the mouse to change your perspective. 
Right click for moving the orbit and wheel for getting away or closer.

Choose your perspective the token will be minted from your own point of view.

  Hope you enjoy it
 Gonz.-

metadata.name: Spiraling
metadata.description:
Look inside of you. What do you feel? What do you say to people when they ask "How's it going?"

There are 3 variations for Spiraling. I call them phases. 

Phase 1 is the most common and has a 70% chance of occurring. This phase is typically fuzzy on the inside and slightly unstable on the outside. 

Phase 2 has a 20% chance of occurring. This phase is the most unstable. 

Phase 3 is the one shown in the preview and has a 10% chance of occurring. It is typically very zen on the inside, and slightly unstable on the outside. 

Each token generates a series of 180 circles using both random values and a noise map based on the base hash. 

---

This is a deterministic version of the phase loop experiments on cliqu.art for you to collect! Each one is unique and can't be generated from the experiments.

metadata.name: Los Generators - Enter The Machine
metadata.description:
From Spain we present our FxHash Genesis, a layered png generative artwork:

Los Generators - Enter The Machine
"100 years ago, a family of inventors trying to break into the metaverse, its 2022 and they made it."

The post-folk band is a rare gem, working tirelessly to get this album to web3, set like clockwork the family of Spanish musician-inventors ensures that their effort was not in vain.

Enter The Machine is a concept album, chronicling the inventiveness of an isolated family, creating trinkets and instruments that would make it possible for their album to be encrypted in 1922 and only surface in 2022, where its unique content can be enjoyed.

Los Generators invite you to discover their universe, presented through several randomized album covers, with different graphics and characters, with more than 900 combination possibilities.

Can you imagine their music?

The code part was created using the P5 library to make the combinations between the ready-made layers and manipulate the pixels, placing the layers overlay on a canvas in the html and creating a noise filter using the 'loadPixel()' function.
A simple function was made to save the canvas when pressing the 'P' key, saving a png in 1000x1000p resolution.

Album cover condition: various.
1000x1000 pixels, PNG, 32 bit.
Metabandz and nt_worm, 2022.

Metabandz is a label releasing album cover nft's for fictional music bands.

Los Generators invite you to discover their universe, presented through several randomized album covers, with different graphics and characters, with more than 900 combination possibilities.

Can you imagine their music?

The code part was created using the P5 library to make the combinations between the ready-made layers and manipulate the pixels, placing the layers overlay on a canvas in the html and creating a noise filter using the 'loadPixel()' function.
A simple function was made to save the canvas when pressing the 'P' key, saving a png in 1000x1000p resolution.

Album cover condition: various.
1000x1000 pixels, PNG, 32 bit.
Metabandz and nt_worm, 2022.

Metabandz is a label releasing album cover nft's for fictional music bands.

metadata.name: Unknown Squigl
metadata.description:
Squigls flowing through the Tezos Blockchain.

Unknown Squigl is created with four different themes: 

Monochrome - Squigls with light shade of random hue 
Complementary - Strokes with complementarish color calculated from background hue
Ukraine - 211° for yellow and 50° for the blue
Grayscale - Random background shade of gray and an opposite shade of gray for the strokes

And a few different versions for offsetting the strokes.

The pixelDensity can be changed with pressing keys 1,2,4 or 8. (8 can be slow!)
Image can be downloaded in live view with pressing key 's'.

Created with P5JS.

hic et squigl / 2022

metadata.name: Fx(Interfaces)
metadata.description:
WGMInterfaces said goodbye to the NFT space a day ago. 

Being an absolute fan of their work, sometimes, taking time for yourself is needed in this space and I know it’s not an easy decision for them. I had so much love for their philosophy and fun at designing this derivative PFP project for the FxHash family as a tribute to the team at WAGMInterfaces.

While they return, let's cherish the derivative in the meantime. 

Behance: www.behance.net/gallery/138404877/Interfaces-WAGMI-Inspired

metadata.name: Organicon, variation I
metadata.description:
Generative art by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut
512 unique generators creating an endless sequence of iterations with fixed features

Organicon, variation I is a slow piece, meant to build on the screen. Warning: the preview thumbnail is a pale shadow of live view.

Interface: a first mouse click clears the screen, creates an new iteration and enables active mode. In active mode each iteration remains on screen for a limited amount of time before being replaced by the next. A second mouse click disables active mode. In active mode a small dot is displayed in the lower right corner. '+' and '-' zoom in and out.

metadata.name: Tree Skyness
metadata.description:
Tree Skyness

Crown shyness occurs when the tops of fully grown trees avoid touching each other, forming gaps in the canopy. This piece simulates that phenomena and plays with celestial object avoidance. Features include four seasons, time of day, up to 12 trees, and many special options. HD rendering can be enabled for 8192x8192 resolution. 10% of primary sales will be donated to the fxhash Ukraine fund.

Click to randomize with the same settings.

By Frank Force @KilledByAPixel
Made with Vanilla JavaScript

Controls
1 = Save a 2048x2048 png (or right click save)
2 = Toggle HD (may not work in some environments)
3 = Toggle noise (disable for clearer image)
